\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 Framing the problem\

\f1\b0 \
0. I'm going to follow the GMT practice of using "quasi" to call attention to the fact that we aren't actually dealing with manifolds, but rather with classes of hyperbolic groups which *might* contain one or more (possibly infinitely many) discrete groups.\
\
1. The starting point is a quasi-relator -- a word which is necessarily a group identity for any manifold in the region\
\
2. Given a quasi-relator, it's straightforward to construct a number of "geometric quasi-MOMs" by following closed paths in the "O(1) cusp graph" whose vertices are centers of horoballs and whose edges are the edges of length equal to O(1).\
\
3. The aim is to convert one of these "geometric quasi-MOMs" into a full topological internal MOM structure and thereby identify a "quasi-parent manifold".  As in GMM2, there are three obstacles:\
	3a. embeddedness\
	3b. torus boundary components\
	3c. fullness\
In this case, the combinatorics of the geometrical MOM structure are fixed, and so it's straightforward to directly compute the boundary components and to show fullness.  Embeddedness is more difficult to show.\
\
